{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_caribou_ver01/data/sn82014189/00279526168/1908042701/0094.xml":{"full_text":"Qje .Alaskan\nOfficial City Paper\nL. S. ^JLLMR, PUBLISHER\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nOne week. delivered fcy -artier 10.26\nOne month, br mall 75\n.Three months, by n?>l 2JS\n9tx months, by mall 4-50\nOne year, by mall 9.00\n0 \"The attitude of courage, good\ncbe.r, health and kindness leads d\nto pleasant pathways.\"\n0.1 E TAX OUTRAGE\nTh* He?vy Ft** Charged Against the\nRoadhoase Kaep*r for Doing tha\nThing nil Men want Him to do\nA wr.ter in the Alaska-Yukon mag\nazine has touched upon a most, timely\ntopio in a most convincing way. He\nsets out on a journey on foot from Fair\nbanks to the mines on Cleary creek?\nand the itory particularly appeals to\nthe editor of the Alaskan since he has\ntraveled that same trail many a time\nhimself. The writer, in his story, toils\nup and up and up to the summit of the\ndifficult divide, the horizon slowly\nbroadening until at the top a m.?gnlfi>\ncent landscape spreads away under bis\neye. He fee^s himself aloje almost in\nc'ouds with the busy mines of Pedro\nand Gold Stream on the one tide and\nthose of Cleary on the other making\ntheir feeble tracings along the distant\ncreeks like so m?ny ant hills in the\ngreat sweep of the picture. But he is\nnot alone. There is a roadhouse near?\nand how it appeals to bini atter the\nwearisome climb. Now to quote the\nmagazine writer:\n\"The ro dhcuse was a large log cabin,\nin the rear of which was she kitchen,\nwhere a woman was baking bread. In\nthe front room was a rude bar, and a few\nchairs and two or three benches where\nthe w?arr might sit and partake of\ntbeir refreshments. The most con\nspuious things in this humble place\nwere the government licenses. They\nmade a big patch on the bare walls back\nof the b>r. I noticed first the name.\nMartin Danielsen, then I read on far\nther. fifteen dollars for the privilege of\nselling tobacco and cigars: just below\nthis on the wall was another license,\nfifteen dollars for the privilege of con\nducting a resiaurant; then there was\nanother license, five hundred dollars for\nprivilege of retailing liquors; and b\nnealu nil this evidence of revenue paid\nto the federal governs ent was the in\nt roal revenue license of twenty-five\ndollars,, making a total of ?>5o, tribute\nmoney that tliis man in his log cabin,\ntwenty miles from an lccorporated\ntown and in a country which but a few\nj ears before was a wilderness, was com\nDelled to pay to the United States lor\nthe privilege of conducting a wayside\ninn.\n?To my mica tncre appears to oe\nsometbiug anomalous io these revenue\nlags and the surroundings. Here was\na log cabio, rudely constructed, several\nmiles distant from the neares' habita\ntion, erected by the loadsiae and on an\nelevation commanding one of the most\nmagnificent views to be bad in Alaska;\nwhere vast expanse of untrodden terri\ntory and great reaches of unexplored\nbill and valley, emphasized the feeling\nof llOerty and lack of restraint which\ncomes to every man when he first visits\nthis country; and yet amid all these\nprimitive conditions our ereat and ben\neficent government was eiactiog a\nquadruple toll from a citizen for the\nprivilege of conducting a wayside Inn.\nIt did not 9eem right, it does not seem\nright now; for that matter any tax upon\nthrift, Ii.dusiry or enterprise does not\nseem right. License lair may be neces\nsary in order to provide revenue. The\nexigencies of business demand things\nthat are not ethical; but I would like to\nsee a license law which would be less\nburdensome to the Alaska roadbouse\nkeeper.\"\nYes and so would many others. The\nIdea of the government fining a man\nlor doing the thing that the travel\ner in the wilderness blesses him for do\ning, seems monstrous. Perhaps, after\nall, the liquor license bill of Governor\nHogg&tt, against which the Alaskan\nprotested some time since is the better\none after ail. It refuses a license to the\nroadhoase keeper entiiely. Of oourse\nevery bedj knows what the reault of\nsuch a measure would be. Those who\nbelieve in law and in tlie respect\n(or and observance of the same, wou'd\nprefer t<j see these things done In rev\nson. But in the faco of Goes like these,\nlevied against men for doing the things\nthat all men want done and which are\nnecessary to be done, the disposition U\nto close ones eyes against the infraction\nof a law which forbids their being done.\nIn the story of the bright business\noutlook told with relation to Juneau\nparticulary, and for all Southeastern\nAlaska in general in an interview in\nSaturday's Alaskan, Skagway buys\n\"hereto.\" Business was never better\nsince the days of the Klondike boom.\nThe arrival of two mall carrying\nsteamers on one day Is still the order of\nthe running no less to the amazement\nthan the irritation of the people of\nSoutheastern Alaska. Such an ur\nrangement ia to the interested but\nhelpless onlooker unfathotmble.\nA RETROSPECTIVE\nBy Rex A. Lampmun\nMy boyhood lies fur, far away\nDown the dim road of Yesterday,\nYet oft the heart within mo cries\nFor just one glimpso of those glad\nskies.\nOf that lest time when hearts were gay.\nWhat joyous c?re-free days were they!\nWhat merry games we used to play !j\n1 gaze back where? ah! how time\nflies\nMy boyhool lies.\nSo n?w, my temples streaked with gray\nI sit and dream of lifetime's May,\nAs Memory old Timejdetits:\nThough smiliog, I cannot despise\nThose master fictions of their day?\nMy boyhood lies.\n?May Smart Set.\n1 PERFECT MAY DAY IN APRIL I\nS\nI LOCAL ANO INTERIOR WEATHER ij\n8 5\nThe result of the observation taken\nat Moore wharf at midnignt, April 26\n1908, is as follows:\nTemperature timeobservat'n.42 above\nMax. temp. preceding 24 hour*. 48 above\nMin. ..42 above\nMean ..45 above\nBarometer 29.88\nKain, Cilm.\nWhitehorse- clear, s wind 22 above.\n.\\tlln? clear, s wind, 37 above.\nCtnter? clear, s wind 33 above.\nCaribou? clear, calm 30 above.\nTagish? clear, calm, 32 above.\nLabarge? clear, s wind 34 above.\nHoo alinqua? clear, s wind, 38 above.\nYukon Crossing? clear, s wind,38 above\nStewart? clear, s wicd 32 above.\nOgilve? clear, calm, 30 above\nDjwson? cloudy, s wind 3\" above.\nBest meals in Whltehorse at Com\nmPif.ml Cafe. tf\nTHE Mir SHIRT SET\nThe Smart Set for M?y opens with a\nbrilliant novelette by Elisabeth R'jblns,\nentitled \"The Will of tne Gods.\" A\nmore unusual stjjfv has seldom been\nprinted in a mtinnzlue.\nIn short fiction the May number Is\nvery strong, There Isf a splendid char\nacter study by Elizabeth Jordan en\ntitled \"Tillie necrotic's Developing\nSoul Miss Jordan has excelled her\nself in this tale. In Stateroom C-5,\"\nby Frauk A. Ward, Is the pathetic\nstory of acrlminal who is being brought\nto America; \"Gossamer Glory,\" by\nMrs. Henry Dudeney, \"is one of this\ndistinguished ICnglish writer's best\nstories; \"The Debt,\" by Arthur Stan\nley Wheeler, is a splendid analyst of\nan event in college professor's life;\n\"The Night of the Wedding,\" by Rich\nard Duffy, is a one-act play of more\nthan ordinary dramatic value; It tells\nsimply yet powerfully, a very human\nstory. \"The Shocking of Felicia,\" by\nCatharine Carr; \"Their Own Kind,\"\nby Kate Masterson; \"The Bomb PlaLt\ners,\" by Alfred Damon Runycn; \"Be\nneath the Surface,\" by Sidney Fred\neiloks, and \"The White Peacock,\" by\nCarr Alison, are other admirable\nstories.\nPILES CURED IN 6 TO 14 DAYS\nPAZO OINTMENT is guaranteed\nto cure any case of itching, Blind,\nBleeding or Protruding Piles iu 6 to 14\ndays or money refunded. 60c\nKEEP YOUR HEAD UNCOVERED.\nConstant Wrirlne of a lint Propo\nuat' ii Dandruff Germs.\nare^many men who wear their\n-actlcally all the time when awake,\nro blessed with a heavy shook Of\n.:v; yet If tho scalps of these same raon\nbecame Infested with dandruff\nrms. the parasites would multiply all\nquicker for lack of air. Baldness\njld ensue as the final result New\nro's Herplcl